did.abstract: Sara Stillman was a photographer for the Michigan Daily from 1995 to 1998. The majority of the collection consists of 35mm negatives of University of Michigan athletics, particularly football and basketball, as well as other University of Michigan and Ann Arbor events.

repository.corpname: Bentley Historical Library, University of Michigan

acqinfo.p: The collection was donated by Sara Stillman (Donor no. 9587) in April 2005.

accessrestrict.p: The collection is open to research.

userestrict.p: Copyright is held by the Regents of the University of Michigan.

prefercite.p: [item], folder, box, Sara Stillman negatives, Bentley Historical Library, University of Michigan

bioghist.p: Sara Stillman was a photographer from 1995 to 1998 for the Michigan Daily, the student newspaper at the University of Michigan.

scopecontent.p: The majority of the collection consists of developed 35mm negatives, housed in protective sheets. The negatives are divided into two series: Athletics and Other Negatives. There are also a few developed photographs and rolls of undeveloped film. Three of the rolls are from a basketball game and the remainder are unidentified.

controlaccess.head: Subjects - Visual Materials:
controlaccess.corpname: University of Michigan--Student life and customs--1990-2000.

scopecontent.p: Athletics (0.75 linear feet, 1995-1998) contains 35mm negatives from a variety of University of Michigan sporting events, the majority being men's basketball, football, and ice hockey. Most of the events are for men's athletics, but also include a few women's events. The negatives are arranged alphabetically by sport and then chronologically.

scopecontent.p: Other Negatives (0.25 linear feet, 1995-1998) includes negatives from University of Michigan and Ann Arbor events. Most of the images relate to the arts, political events and student activities. Of special note are the negatives related to affirmative action, the pro/affirmative action organization BAMN (By Any Means Necessary) and the celebration of Martin Luther King, Jr. Day. The negatives are arranged alphabetically by topic.
